{
  "answer": "**In the Falsafa corpus, \"Tarana-e-Hindi\" (also known as \"Sare Jahan se Accha\") appears as the patriotic \"Hindustani Bachon Ka Qaumi Geet\" (\"National Anthem of Indian Children\") in Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*.**[^1] The speaker's belonging is most clearly defined in the final stanza, which celebrates the land as an eternal paradise embodying its people (likened to Moses), peaks (Sinai's heights, evoking hills), sacred ground (implying rivers and landscapes through biblical imagery of arks and heavenly stairs), and divine homeland: \"Its people Moses, and its peaks are Sinai's height, / Where Prophet Noah's ark first saw the light, / Whose very ground is a stair to heaven's light, / To live here is a paradise of pure delight, / This is my homeland, this land of mine.\"[^2]\n\n**\"Widsith,\" from *Old English Elegies* (chapter 14), frames the speaker's identity through his lineage and endless wandering among warbands, lords, and remembered halls across tribes.**[^3] The defining moment comes early, tying him to the Myrgings' people and their comitatus (warband) traditions: \"Widsith spoke, unlocked his word-hoard, / he who of men had journeyed through most tribes / and peoples over the earth... From the Myrgings / his lineage arose.\"[^4] This roots him not in fixed geography but in a portable social network of halls, gifts, and heroic catalogs—later evoked in his pursuit of Eormanric's \"household war-band\" amid transient kings and battles.[^5]\n\n**The speaker of *Tarana-e-Hindi*'s belonging to place—its enduring hills, riverscapes, and mythic people—is harder to lose.** Iqbal's land is cosmic and immutable, a \"rampart\" and \"stair to heaven\" outlasting conquerors (echoed in *Himalaya* as Hindustan's eternal sentinel).[^6] Widsith's ties to warbands and halls, however, are fragile: they scatter with exile, defeat, or death, as the poem itself laments through its lists of fallen rulers.[^7] A physical homeland persists in memory and geography; a comitatus dissolves when spears fly and lords fail.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 26 (\"Hindustani Bachon Ka Qaumi Geet\"), translation, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/26-hindustani-bachon-ka-qaumi-geet/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Ibid., [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/26-hindustani-bachon-ka-qaumi-geet/translation/#p-a9f72d).\n\n[^3]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, ch. 14 (\"Widsith matholade, wordhord onleac\"), translation, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/14-widsith-matholade-wordhord-onleac/translation/).\n\n[^4]: Ibid., [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/14-widsith-matholade-wordhord-onleac/translation/#p-2f6bd3).\n\n[^5]: Ibid., [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/14-widsith-matholade-wordhord-onleac/translation/#p-41b132).\n\n[^6]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 25 (\"Himalaya\"), translation, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/25-himalaya/translation/#p-b8c905).\n\n[^7]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, ch. 14, translation, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/14-widsith-matholade-wordhord-onleac/translation/#p-545201).",
